documentation: The `#;` preprocessor directive creates a single line comment that does not appear in .int code.

label: #Def1Arg
documentation: The `#Def1Arg` preprocessor directive defines a macro with only one argument, where that argument can have commas in it.

label: #Define
documentation: The `#Define` preprocessor directive defines a macro.

label: #Dim
documentation: The `#Dim` preprocessor directive specifies the intended data type of a local variable and can optionally specify its initial value.

label: #Else
documentation: The `#Else` preprocessor directive specifies the beginning of the fall-through case in a set of preprocessor conditions.

label: #ElseIf
documentation: The `#ElseIf` preprocessor directive specifies the beginning of a secondary case in a set of preprocessor conditions that begin with `#If`.

label: #ElIf
documentation: Alternate name of `#ElseIf`.

label: #EndIf
documentation: The `#EndIf` preprocessor directive concludes a set of preprocessor conditions.

label: #Execute
documentation: The `#Execute` preprocessor directive executes a line of ObjectScript at compile time.

label: #If
documentation: The `#If` preprocessor directive begins a block of conditional text.

label: #IfDef
documentation: The `#IfDef` preprocessor directive marks the beginning of a block of conditional code where execution depends on a macro having been defined.

label: #IfNDef
documentation: The `#IfNDef` preprocessor directive marks the beginning of a block of conditional code where execution depends on a macro having not been defined.

label: #IfUnDef
documentation: Alternate name of `#IfNDef`.

label: #Import
documentation: The `#Import` preprocessor directive specifies the schema search path for any subsequent Embedded SQL DML statements.

label: #Include
documentation: The `#Include` preprocessor directive loads a specified file name that contains preprocessor directives.

label: #NoShow
documentation: The `#NoShow` preprocessor directive ends a comment section that is part of an include file.

label: #Show
documentation: The `#Show` preprocessor directive begins a comment section that is part of an include file.

label: #SQLCompile Audit
documentation: The `#SQLCompile Audit` preprocessor directive is a boolean that specifies whether any subsequent Embedded SQL statements should be audited.

label: #SQLCompile Path
documentation: The `#SQLCompile Path` preprocessor directive specifies the schema search path for any subsequent Embedded SQL DML statements.

label: #SQLCompile Select
documentation: The `#SQLCompile Select` preprocessor directive specifies the data format mode for any subsequent Embedded SQL statements.

label: #UnDef
documentation: The `#UnDef` preprocessor directive removes the definition for an already-defined macro.
The `##;` preprocessor directive makes the remaining part of the current line a comment that does not appear in .int code.

label: ##Continue
documentation: The `##Continue` preprocessor directive continues a macro definition on the next line, to support multiline macro definitions.

label: ##Expression
documentation: The `##Expression` preprocessor function evaluates an ObjectScript expression at compile time.

label: ##Function
documentation: The `##Function` preprocessor function evaluates an ObjectScript function at compile time.

label: ##Lit
documentation: The `##Lit` preprocessor function preserves the content of its argument in literal form.

label: ##Quote
documentation: The `##Quote` preprocessor function takes a single argument and returns that argument quoted.

label: ##QuoteExp
documentation: The `##QuoteExp` preprocessor function takes as an argument an expression that gets evaluated during compilation.

label: ##SQL
documentation: The `##SQL` preprocessor directive invokes a specified Embedded SQL statement at runtime.

label: ##StripQ
documentation: The `##StripQ` preprocessor function takes a single argument and returns that argument with quotes removed.

label: ##Unique
documentation: The `##Unique` preprocessor function creates a new, unique local variable within a macro definition for use at compile time or runtime.
